# SOP Governance Model

## Overview

Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) document the processes that guide operational workflows within wholesale organizations. SOP governance ensures these procedures remain accurate, accessible, and aligned with current operational practices.

---

## Purpose

SOP governance helps organizations:

• standardize operational processes  
• maintain consistent execution across teams  
• reduce training gaps  
• support operational scalability  
• ensure process documentation remains current

Strong SOP governance allows teams to operate with clear expectations and consistent practices.

---

## SOP Components

Effective SOP documentation typically includes:

• process purpose  
• step-by-step workflow instructions  
• responsible roles  
• required systems or tools  
• operational checkpoints  
• escalation paths  

These elements help teams execute workflows correctly.

---

## SOP Lifecycle

SOPs typically move through several stages:

1. process identification  
2. SOP creation  
3. stakeholder review  
4. operational approval  
5. implementation  
6. periodic review and updates  

Maintaining this lifecycle ensures documentation stays relevant.

---

## Ownership

SOP ownership should be clearly defined.

Common owners include:

• operations managers  
• process improvement teams  
• functional team leads  

Ownership ensures procedures remain aligned with operational realities.

---

## Documentation Accessibility

SOPs should be accessible to the teams responsible for executing them. Many organizations maintain SOP libraries within internal documentation systems or knowledge management platforms.

Accessible documentation helps teams resolve operational questions quickly.

---

## Final Note

SOP governance ensures that operational knowledge is captured, standardized, and maintained. When organizations document processes effectively, they reduce operational variability and support long-term scalability.
